Improve your workflow with web APIs


In this lesson, we will be accessing data via web APIs (Application Programming Interfaces). This process improves workflow by avoiding the potentially repetitive data acquisition process of finding and downloading data using a web browser. Using a web API to access data can also lead to a more reproducible workflow, as your scripts can include how you collected your data, rather than simply what you did with it.


Set up

Please load the following libraries prior to continuing with this session. If one of the libraries is not currently installed on your computer (Error in library(jpeg) : there is no package called ...), use the function install.packages() to get the package. Remember that every package that is installed also needs to be loaded (library())!

Introduction to reading data from a web API:


We will start by talking directly to an API using the R package httr. We will query the Open Movie Database (OMDb) API to load and explore movie data.

Lets contact OMDb and query the database for the movie Zoolander: 

zoo_url <-
  'http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=6fa7876b&t=Zoolander'


Lets take moment to explore the url above:

  • http://: This is the internet protocol (in this case the unsecure Hypertext transfer protocol.
  • www.omdbapi.com: This is the domain (hostname).
  • ?: This initiates our query.
  • apikey=6fa7876b: This provides the server with out API key (which provides us with access to the data.
  • &: This allows us to provide an additional argument to the server
  • t=Zoolander: This is our query, which queries based on the parameter t, which stands for the title of the movie.

Note that the above demonstrates that it is important to know the parameters used to query a servers database. Its generally necessary to look at the metadata of an API prior to submitting a request (take a look at the Parameters section of the OMDb).


We can now use the http verb GET to read the data from the OMDb API: 

api_data <- 
  httr::GET(zoo_url)


What did that return? Lets look at api_data: 

api_data
## Response [http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=6fa7876b&t=Zoolander]
##   Date: 2021-10-12 13:02
##   Status: 200
##   Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8
##   Size: 911 B


The above tells us the response to our request, returning:

  • The request
  • The date and time the request was received
  • A status message indicating whether the request was successful (200 indicates success see status codes)
  • The type of content that is returned
  • The amount of data returned (better have some data in there!)


To look at the data that was returned, explore the following using the httr::content() function. The argument of the function as describes the format of the data you that would like to use. 

# extract the content:

httr::content(api_data, as = 'raw')

httr::content(api_data, as = 'text')

httr::content(api_data, as = 'parsed')

The default of this function is as = NULL, which tries to automatically determine the most appropriate content type (see ?httr::content) 

api_content <-
  httr::content(api_data)

Lets look at the content. Well start by looking at the structure (str) of the output:

We can see that our request returned a list composed of a lot of different classes of list items (including more lists!). Lets view the names of the list items: 

names(api_content)
##  [1] "Title"      "Year"       "Rated"      "Released"   "Runtime"   
##  [6] "Genre"      "Director"   "Writer"     "Actors"     "Plot"      
## [11] "Language"   "Country"    "Awards"     "Poster"     "Ratings"

As with all list objects, we can use indexing to query the list. Lets query the list by the item named Plot: 

api_content[['Plot']]
## [1] "At the end of his career, a clueless fashion model is brainwashed to kill the Prime Minister of Malaysia."

We can create a tibble of api content that we want to look at: 

tibble(
  title = api_content[['Title']],
  year = api_content[['Year']],
  plot = api_content[['Plot']],
  poster = api_content[['Poster']]
)
## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##   title   year  plot                            poster                          
##   <chr>   <chr> <chr>                           <chr>                           
## 1 Zoolan 2001  At the end of his career, a cl https://m.media-amazon.com/imag

Because these items are objects in a list, this is a great use of mapping with purrr! Well use purrr::map_dfc to create a data frame by binding the output as columns: 

# Because these items are objects in a list, this is a great use of map!

purrr::map_dfc(
  c('Title', 'Year', 'Plot', 'Poster'),
  function(x) {
    tibble(
      api_content[[x]]) %>%
      set_names(x)
  }
)

We can also use purrr to string together multiple API calls: 

# string together multiple api calls --------------------------------------

movies <-
  c('Zoolander',
    'Harold+and+Maude',
    'The+Life+Aquatic',
    'Idiocracy',
    'The+Royal+Tenenbaums')

api <- 
  'http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=6fa7876b&t='

# Use purrr::map_dfr to query the database by the movies vector:

movie_frame <-
  purrr::map_dfr(
  movies,
  function(x) {
    api_content <-
      # construct request:
      str_c(api, movie_title) %>%
      # make request to api: 
      httr::GET() %>%
      # get content:
      httr::content()
    tibble(
      title = api_content$Title,
      year = api_content$Year,
      plot = api_content$Plot,
      poster = api_content$Poster
    )
  })

# what did we get?

movie_frame

View(movie_frame)

The above could have been simplified by using a map function, as below. Theres a function from the magrittr package (loaded with tidyverse) called extract that allows us to pull just the variables of interest from a list. 

api <- 
  'http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=6fa7876b&t='

purrr::map_dfr(
  c(
    'Zoolander',
    'Harold+and+Maude',
    'The+Life+Aquatic',
    'Idiocracy',
    'The+Royal+Tenenbaums'),
  function(x) {
    str_c(api, x) %>%
      # make request to api: 
      httr::GET() %>%
      # get content:
      httr::content() %>%
      # extract variables of interest:
      magrittr::extract(c('Title', 'Year', 'Plot', 'Poster'))
  })
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   Title          Year  Plot                         Poster                      
##   <chr>          <chr> <chr>                        <chr>                       
## 1 Zoolander      2001  At the end of his career, a https://m.media-amazon.com/
## 2 Harold and Ma 1971  Young, rich, and obsessed w https://m.media-amazon.com/
## 3 The Life Aqua 2004  With a plan to exact reveng https://m.media-amazon.com/
## 4 Idiocracy      2006  Private Joe Bauers, a decis https://m.media-amazon.com/
## 5 The Royal Ten 2001  The eccentric members of a  https://m.media-amazon.com/

Application: Using the rinat package to query the iNaturalist API



The iNaturalist project is an amazing citizen science project from the California Acadamy of Sciences and the National Geographic Society (learn more here). At the time of this writing, there are nearly 700,000 iNaturalist users that have submitted 25 million observations of 230,000 different species.


The Susquehanna


Lets start by using httr::GET() to query to iNaturalist API for observations were recorded in the Susquehanna River Basinin 2018.

susquehanna <-
  httr::GET('http://www.inaturalist.org/observations.csv?q=susquehanna&year=2018')  %>%
  httr::content()


The query returned a very wide dataframe (38 columns) with only 30 records. We can increase the number of records returned using the per_page parameter: 

susquehanna <-
  httr::GET('http://www.inaturalist.org/observations.csv?q=susquehanna&year=2018&per_page=200')  %>%
  httr::content()

We can use names() to determine the names of the resultant tibble. We can use dplyr::select() to subset the tibble to only the variables of interest: 

susquehanna <-
  httr::GET('http://www.inaturalist.org/observations.csv?q=susquehanna&year=2018&per_page=200')  %>%
  httr::content() %>%
  dplyr::select(
    c(
      'user_id',
      'user_login',
      'observed_on',
      'common_name',
      'scientific_name',
      'longitude',
      'latitude',
      'description'
      ))


R Users have built packages to assist in querying and getting data from APIs. The package rinat helps us construct queries for the iNaturalist API. Lets try to recreate our query of iNaturalist observations in the Susquehanna River Basin in 2018. There are lots of observations in the iNaturalist database, so we will use the maxresults argument to return a maximum of 200 results. 

susquehanna <-
  get_inat_obs(
    query = 'susquehanna',
    year = 2018,
    maxresults = 200) %>%
  as_tibble()

The Brown-headed cowbird


There are lots of arguments that you can use with the rinat package that can help you narrow down your results. See ?rinat::get_inat_obs for a complete list. In the below, lets query the iNaturalist API to observations that were: of the taxon Molothrus ater (Brown-headed cowbird), made in 2018, of research quality, and at georeferenced locations. 

get_inat_obs(
  taxon_name = "Molothrus ater",
  year = 2018,
  quality = 'research',
  geo = TRUE,
  maxresults = 500) %>%
  as_tibble()

Are Green darners migratory?


After dinner one night at the Smithsonian-Mason School of Conservation campus, several students and I spotted some huge dragonflies that we assumed were Green darners (Anax junius). We wondered whether or not they were migratory. While we could have figured this out with a search engine, I thought it might be fun to observe their migration with the data.

Lets start by querying the iNaturalist API for Green darners with a bounding box of c(24, -125, 50, -66) (roughly the continental US), the year 2018, and the month of September: 

get_inat_obs(
  taxon_name = "Anax junius",
  year = 2018,
  month = 9,
  geo = TRUE,
  bounds = c(24, -125, 50, -66)
)


Take a moment to explore the data frame that the query above returns.

We can build a for loop to generate a list, with each list item the observations of Green darners for a given month: 

gDarner_monthList <-
  vector('list', length = 12)

for(i in 1:12) {
  gDarner_monthList[[i]] <-
    get_inat_obs(
      taxon_name = "Anax junius",
      year = 2018,
      month = i,
      geo = TRUE,
      bounds = c(24, -125, 50, -66)
    )
}


We can plot a single map of observations as follows: 

map_data('usa') %>%
  ggplot(
    aes(x = long,
        y = lat)) +
  geom_polygon(
    aes(group = group),
    fill = 'white') +
  borders('state') +
  geom_point(
    data = gDarner_monthList[[9]],
    aes(x = longitude, y = latitude)) +
  xlim(-125, -65) +
  ylim(25, 50) +
  labs(title = month.name[9]) +
  theme(
    title = element_text(size = rel(1.4)))


We can use purrr::map() to watch Green darner migration! 

purrr::map(
  1:12,
  function(i) {
    map_data('usa') %>%
      ggplot(
        aes(x = long, 
            y = lat)) +
      geom_polygon(
        aes(group = group),
        fill = 'white') +      
      borders('state') +
      geom_point(
        data = gDarner_monthList[[i]],
        aes(x = longitude, y = latitude)) +
      xlim(-125, -65) +
      ylim(25, 50) +
      labs(title = month.name[i])) +
  theme(
    title = element_text(size = rel(1.4))
  )})


You can use ImageMagick to generate a GIF of Green darner observations over time. Heres how to create the GIF (make sure that you have installed ImageMagick onto your computer!): 

# Clear plot window:

plot.new()

# Open a connection to write png files:

png('gDarner_%02d.png', 
    width = 800, 
    height = 500)

# Map to run across each month:

purrr::map(
  1:12,
  function(i) {
    map_data('usa') %>%
      ggplot(
        aes(x = long,
            y = lat)) +
      geom_polygon(
        aes(group = group), 
        fill = 'white',
        color = 'gray40',
        size = 0.2) +
      borders('state') +
      geom_point(
        data = gDarner_monthList[[i]],
        aes(x = longitude, y = latitude),
        size = 2) +
      xlim(-125, -65) +
      ylim(25, 50) +
      labs(title = month.name[i]) +
      theme(
        title = element_text(size = rel(1.4))
      )
  })

# Close png device:

dev.off()

list.files(pattern = "*.png", full.names = T) %>% 
  # Read each file in the path:
  purrr::map(
    magick::image_read) %>%
  # Join images together:
  magick::image_join() %>% 
  # Animate, defining frames per second:
  magick::image_animate(fps=1) %>% 
  # Write to file:
  magick::image_write("gDarner.gif")

Application: Using the robis package to query the OBIS API


The The Ocean Biogeographic Information System (OBIS) is an amazing resource where users can retrieve and submit biogeographic data relating to the worlds oceans. OBIS contains over 50 million recorded observations of marine species!

We will contact the OBIS to query observations of Sperm whale (Physeter macrocephalus). Lets first user httr::GET() to contact the OBIS API directly: 

httr::GET('https://api.obis.org/v3/occurrence?scientificname=Physeter+macrocephalus&size=200') %>%
  httr::content()

Have a look at the resultant object. Its pretty difficult to read, yeah? In fact, to get even get the names of the object, we have to dive pretty far into the list: 

httr::GET('https://api.obis.org/v3/occurrence?scientificname=Physeter+macrocephalus&size=200') %>%
  httr::content() %>%
  .[['results']] %>%
  .[[1]] %>%
  names()

Luckily, there is an R Package, robis, that can help us get and format data from the OBIS API. Using the function robis::occurrence(), its easy to write a query. Lets pull observations of Sperm whales from 2018: 

sperm_whale <- 
  occurrence(
    scientificname = 'Physeter macrocephalus',
    startdate = '2018-01-01',
    enddate = '2019-01-01')
## Retrieved 228 records of approximately 228 (100%)

Theres even a custom function for plotting OBIS data in an interactive Leaflet map: 

map_leaflet(
  sperm_whale,
  provider_tiles = 'OpenStreetMap')
